{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "wittgenstein-expert",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Real problem — use inline literal gloss in this one sentence, TN at first occurrence",
    "content": "1. **Yes, it is a real problem here.** Not in general -- most of the time \"the metaphysical\" works fine. But in *this specific sentence*, the author is using the internal structure of 形而上 as a philosophical argument: the word itself encodes the spatial metaphor (above/below) that the author is about to deconstruct. If the reader cannot see that \"the metaphysical\" literally means \"above the phenomenal,\" they miss that the very *terminology* embeds the top-down assumption the author is dismantling.\n\n2. **A TN is necessary regardless of what we do with the main text.** The 形/形而上/形而上学 distinction is the first entry point into the author's entire framework. This is already noted in the dictionary (Essay 1 appendix, lines 91-97, where the author explains the etymology from the Yijing). A TN at first occurrence of 形而上 should cover this.\n\n3. **Do not use \"above-the-phenomenal\" in running text.** It is too clunky and will not survive repetition. Instead, keep \"the metaphysical\" in the running text but handle *this specific sentence* with a hybrid rendering:\n\n> \"Thus Dao is the highest -- it is *the metaphysical* (形而上, literally 'above form'); while ritual conduct is the lowest -- it is *form* itself (形).\"\n\nThe parenthetical literal gloss appears only here, in the one sentence where the etymology does argumentative work. Everywhere else, plain \"the metaphysical.\" The TN at first occurrence can then expand: \"形而上 (*xing er shang*, literally 'that which is above form/phenomena'): the author reinterprets 形 as phenomena (现象), making 形而上 'that which is constructed upon phenomena.' See Appendix.\"\n\nThis keeps the running text clean while preserving the etymological argument exactly where it matters."
  }
}
